When you use 'REP STOSB' (or 'REP' with any of the string instructions), ECX is decemented automatically, by 1, for each memory access the instruction makes. 
And once ECX gets itself decremented down to 0, 'REP STOSB' detects that ECX is now 0 and stops firing into memory. 
Control them passes on to the next instrution in line. 
But take away 'REP', and the automatic decementing of ECX stops. 
So also, does the automatic detection of when ECX has been counted down to 0. 
Something has to decement ECX, as ECX governs how many toimes the string instructions accesses memory. 
If 'STOSB' doesn't do it - you guessed it - you have to do it somewhere else, with another instruction. 
The obvious way to decement ECX is to use "DEC ECX"; and the obvious way to determine whether ECX has been decemented to 0 is to follow 'DEC ECX' insturction with a 'JNZ' (Jump if Not Zero) instruction. 
'JNZ' test the Zero flag, ZF, and jumps back to the 'STOSB' instruction until ZF becomes true. 
And ZF becomes true when a 'DEC' instrucion causes its operand (ECX) to become 0.
